SuperMap tutorial

In this tutorial, we demonstrate how to use SuperMap for integrative analyses of unpaired single-cell multimodal data. Here, we showcase an example of integrating RNA and ATAC modality. We use a publicly available 10X Multimodal PBMC dataset download from 10X Genomics website, which contains scRNA-seq and scATAC-seq profiles.

Necessary packages

To run this vignette, please ensure that the following packages are installed:

library(SuperMap)
library(Seurat)
library(Signac)
library(GenomicRanges)
library(GenomeInfoDb)
library(EnsDb.Hsapiens.v86)

Stage 1: Data Preparation

We begin by loading the downloaded data, which includes scRNA-seq and scATAC-seq measurements. Both datasets are provided as count matrices, with cells as columns and features as rows.

## Read data from the file
rna_counts =  readRDS('rna_counts.RDS')
atac_counts = readRDS('atac_counts.RDS')

First, we create separate Seurat objects for the RNA and ATAC data, and then perform preprocessing for each modality.

#RNA object
rna_seurat = CreateSeuratObject(counts = rna_counts,assay = 'RNA')    ## Creat SeuratObject

#ATAC object
annotations = GetGRangesFromEnsDb(ensdb = EnsDb.Hsapiens.v86)
seqlevels(annotations) = paste0('chr', seqlevels(annotations))
genome(annotations) = "hg38"
atac_seurat = CreateChromatinAssay(counts = atac_counts,sep = c("-", "-"),annotation = annotations, fragments = 'pbmc_granulocyte_sorted_10k_atac_fragments.tsv.gz')
## Computing hash
atac_seurat = CreateSeuratObject(counts = atac_seurat,assay = "ATAC")

Next, for the RNA modality, we perform data normalization and dimensional reduction for visualization, following the Seurat workflow. If you are unfamiliar with this workflow, please refer to their official tutorial.

rna_seurat = NormalizeData(object = rna_seurat,scale.factor = 10^6)
## Normalizing layer: counts
rna_seurat = FindVariableFeatures(rna_seurat,nfeatures = 3000)
## Finding variable features for layer counts
rna_seurat = ScaleData(rna_seurat)
## Centering and scaling data matrix
rna_seurat = RunPCA(rna_seurat,features = VariableFeatures(object = rna_seurat),verbose = FALSE)
rna_seurat = FindNeighbors(object = rna_seurat, reduction = 'pca', dims = 1:50)
## Computing nearest neighbor graph

Stage 2: Meta-cell construction

In practice, single-cell data are highly sparse and noisy, with an inherently low signal-to-noise ratio. This poses challenges for both model fitting and imputation, making it difficult for the model to capture reliable predictive signals. To address this, SuperMap adopts meta-cell partitioning strategy, a widely used approach to enhance the signal-to-noise ratio in single-cell data by aggregating closely similar cells into meta-cells. For more details, please refer to our paper. Next, we demonstrate how to construct the meta-cell data.

## The resolution parameter can be adjusted flexibly, as it determines the graining level of the resulting meta-cells. Meta-cell graining levels within a reasonable range (25105) are generally feasible. For more details, please refer to our paper.

rna_seurat_meta = metacell_construct(object = rna_seurat, resolution = 25, graph.name = 'RNA_snn')

atac_seurat_meta = metacell_construct(object = atac_seurat, resolution = 25, graph.name = 'ATAC_snn')

metacell_rna <- metacell_matrix_RNA(object = rna_seurat_meta,cluster.name = "seurat_clusters")
metacell_atac <- metacell_matrix_ATAC(object = atac_seurat_meta,cluster.name = "seurat_clusters")

At this point, we obtained metacell-level data for model fitting to estimate cross-modal mappings.

Stage 3: Computing peak-gene distance

When integrating scRNA-seq and scATAC-seq data, SuperMap incorporates genomic proximity as prior knowledge to regularize the model (see our paper for details). Therefore, it is necessary to compute the genomic distances between genes in the RNA modality and peaks in the ATAC modality. We extract highly variable genes for subsequent analysis; however, if you have additional genes of interest, you may include them as well.

## Read the genomic coordinates of genes.
gene_annotation = read.table('~/pbmc_pair_cpm/GRCh38_cellranger2020.gene_location.txt',sep = ' ',header = TRUE)   

variable_gene = VariableFeatures(rna_seurat,assay = 'RNA')
metacell_rna = metacell_rna[,variable_gene]

supermap_data = gene_peak_distance(rna = metacell_rna, atac = metacell_atac, gene_annotation = gene_annotation)

Stage 4: Model fitting for estimating cross-modal mappings

At this stage, we fit the model to learn the cross-modal mappings using the preprocessed data generated above.

learned_mappings = supermap(input_data = supermap_data)

The returned results include both the models convergence information and the estimated parameters. We first visualize the convergence curve from this run to examine the iteration process.

loss = learned_mappings$convergence
loss = as.data.frame(loss)

colnames(loss) = c('residual','objective')
loss$iter = c(1:nrow(loss))

plot(loss$objective)

We observed that the objective function steadily converged over iterations.

Stage 4: Imputating missing-modality profiles

After estimating B, we proceed to impute the missing (unmeasured) modality profiles in unpaired data for subsequent analyses. For imputation, SuperMap provides options at both meta-cell and single-cell resolution to accommodate different downstream analysis tasks. Below, we demonstrate how to predict RNA expression from chromatin accessibility.

## Meta-cell imputation
imputation_metacell = imputation(supermap_data = supermap_data, learned_mappings = learned_mappings, atac_data = atac_seurat, resolution = 'meta-cell')

##Single-cell imputation
imputation_singlecell = imputation(supermap_data = supermap_data, learned_mappings = learned_mappings, atac_data = atac_seurat, resolution = 'single-cell')
## Computing nearest neighbor graph
## Computing SNN

The imputed profiles enable a wide range of downstream analyses of unpaired data, including cell annotation, diagonal integration, regulatory inference, and trajectory analysis, thereby providing valuable biological insights. Next, we visualize the imputed expression patterns of several representative marker genes to facilitate cell annotation.

cell_umap = atac_seurat@reductions$umap@cell.embeddings
cell_umap = as.data.frame(cell_umap)

cell_umap$imputed_value = imputation_singlecell[rownames(cell_umap),'RBM47']
marker_plot(cell_umap = cell_umap)

cell_umap$imputed_value = imputation_singlecell[rownames(cell_umap),'PRF1']
marker_plot(cell_umap = cell_umap)

cell_umap$imputed_value = imputation_singlecell[rownames(cell_umap),'LRRK2']
marker_plot(cell_umap = cell_umap)

Stage 5: Performing diagonal integration

We designed a diagonal integration scheme that harnesses the complementary strengths of both SuperMap and Seurat. Specifically, Seurat calculates the gene activity score from ATAC databased on genomic coordinatesto serve as the linkage for aligning RNA and ATAC modalities. The cross-modal mappings learned by SuperMap enable us to impute the missing RNA profiles for ATAC cells at single-cell level, as described above. Within the Seurat pipeline, we replace the relatively coarse gene activity score with more informative and accurate SuperMap-imputed profiles as linkages, thereby achieving improved modality alignment. In the following, we demonstrate how to perform diagonal integration using SuperMap.

integration_result = diagonal_integration(rna_data = rna_seurat,atac_imputation = imputation_singlecell,rna_label = cell_type)
